                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p><ref target="https://www.archaeology.ie/archaeological-survey-ireland/historic-environment-viewer-application">National Monuments Service</ref> SMR ID: <idno type="SMR">CO085-067008-</idno></p> 
                                    <material type="stone">Sandstone</material> <!--Parkes/Moffat: Fine-grained sandstone-->
                                    <objectType key="monument">Pillar</objectType> 
                                     <dimensions unit="m" source="3d_data">                                        
                                            <height>1.09</height>
                                            <width>0.27</width>
                                            <depth>0.30</depth>
                                     </dimensions>                                   
                                </support>
                                <condition>A very smooth pillar, triangular in horizontal section, reused as a lintel in a souterrain. Macalister (1945, 100-101) describes it as a palimpsest, saying that the original inscription is almost entirely erased. There is certainly damage to the edges of this stone and while it is possible that an earlier inscription has been destroyed, no clear evidence of survives.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">Up on the dexter angle of one of the faces (Macalister's face B), which occupies the space between 0.20m and 0.40m (7.8in. and 15.7in.)  above the stand.</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The surviving ogham stokes on this stone are finely <rs type="execution" key="scored">scored</rs> and described by Macalister (1945, 101) as <q>a mere graffito</q> and <q>roughly scratched</q>. One of the characters was read by Macalister as a rare I-<foreign xml:lang="ga">forfid</foreign>, but this is unclear. He also noted what he describes as an older inscription (cut in <q>bold, well-spaced</q> strokes) on the sinister angle of one of the faces (up-top-down). However, there is no apparent evidence for this.<height/>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
